l},"tags":["author","extraordinary_longevity","educator"],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM920"},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["literature","education"],"notable_blurb":"Wrote 27 books; Newbery Honor author","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olivia_Coolidge","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"education":[{"institution_id":null,"school_name":"Somerville College, Oxford","dates":"1931","type":"undergraduate","notes":"B.A. Classics and Philosophy"},{"institution_id":null,"school_name":"Oxford University","dates":"1940","type":"graduate","notes":"M.A."}],"career":[{"role":"Teacher of Greek, Latin, English","organization":"Schools in Germany, England, and the U.S.","start_year":1931,"end_year":1946},{"role":"Author","organization":"Houghton Mifflin and others","start_year":1949,"end_year":1976}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"literature","header":"She made the ancient world speak to children","body":"Daughter of the British historian Sir Robert Ensor, Olivia Coolidge taught classics before publishing twenty-seven books, beginning with \"Greek Myths\" in 1949. Her retellings brought Homer and the Greek legends to generations of young readers."},{"number":2,"category":"literature","header":"A Newbery honor and a shelf of lives","body":"Her \"Men of Athens\" was a 1963 Newbery Honor book, and she wrote young-adult biographies of Churchill, Gandhi, Edith Wharton, Eugene O’Neill, and Tom Paine. Critics praised her objective scholarship that credited genius without hiding its flaws."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"She married into a Harvard dynasty at thirty-eight","body":"In 1946 the London-born classicist married Archibald Cary Coolidge of Connecticut, a widower with four children, and became a naturalized American. She wrote on into her nineties, living to ninety-eight."}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6606","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1946,"children_ids":[]}],"videos":[{"video_id":"VID015"}],"slug":"margaret-olivia-ensor-